The HACCP system has been obligatory for catering more than a year, but most cafes and restaurants in St. Petersburg have not yet been implemented.
Inspections are becoming more active, and businesses face fines of up to 1 million rubles.
For more than a year, Hazard Analysis and Critical Control Points (HACCP, in the Russian version of HACCP) - risk analysis and critical control points - are mandatory for food manufacturers and carriers, as well as catering companies in Russia as a member of the Customs Union (CU).
Business checks by Rospotrebnadzor for compliance with these standards in St. Petersburg began in February 2015.
But while officials write out fines only for certain violations of the regulations (see "List of documents" ...).
Failure to comply with the regulations as a whole will cost the company 600 thousand rubles for the first violation and 1 million rubles for the second.
HACCP as a system that takes into account risks when working with food products and prevents them, was invented in the USA in the 1960s.
Then it was about food safety for astronauts.
Now the system is used at all food enterprises not only in the USA, but also in Canada and in the European Union.
Since February 2015, HACCP operates on the territory of the CU.
The development and implementation of the system in business was 4 years (HACCP requirements appeared in the technical regulations of the Customs Union in 2011).
However, entrepreneurs and officials alike admit that most companies have not even heard of this norm.
We, unfortunately, for a long time were sure that the norm concerns only food production, not restaurateurs, "explained the head of the Public Council Elena Tsereteli.
Now everyone is trying to catch up.
