French court rejects proposal to demolish stores in Jungle refugee camp
The French court rejected the proposal of the authorities of Calais to demolish dozens of self-made shops and restaurants in the Jungle camp, where thousands of refugees live.
At the court hearings this week, the authorities of Kale said that the state should be able to demolish a total of 72 self-made shops where people inside the camp sell goods, from cigarettes to energy drinks, offer a haircut or sell tea for 50 cents (40p) or the simplest dishes for a few euros in self-made restaurants.
Kale prefecture expressed that these places should be demolished, because they represent a parallel economy that does not pay taxes, and because they carry fire and sanitary risks.
Humanitarian groups told the court that shops and restaurants are vital, stating that the free dishes offered by the pro-government association and other groups do not provide enough food for the growing numbers in the camp.
They argued that self-made shops and restaurants often provide shelter and free food for those who need it.
The Lille court ruled that there was no legal basis to expel people running 72 self-made shops, but stated that the problems of the Calais prefecture "were completely understandable."
Judge Jean-Francois Molla said that groceries, cafes and restaurants played a much larger role than simply feeding people who "live in extremely precarious conditions."
He said that the spaces provided peaceful meeting points for refugees and volunteers.
One of the places that was threatened with demolition was the children's cafe The Jungle Book at the camp, which does not work for profit and offers 200 meals a day, classes in English and French and counseling for asylum for hundreds of vulnerable juveniles unaccompanied in the camp.
Over 170,000 people signed a petition to protect the children's cafe.
A letter sent to the Guardian said that its closure "would be a disaster for these children, some of whom are not older than eight years old."
Two charities, Aid to the Refugees and L'Auberge des Migrants on Friday estimated that the number in the Jungle camp grew and exceeded 9,000 people - the highest in the history - after a sharp increase in new arrivals during the summer.
