The UN is investigating the use of chemical weapons in Syria.
The UN Special Commission is investigating the possible use of toxic gas in the rebel-held areas of the Syrian city of Aleppo.
All parties to the conflict deny the use of chlorine, but the United Nations special envoy for Syria Steffan de Mistura believes that the incident was undeniable.
Similar statements were made on the eve of the third round of the inter-Syrian talks, which should begin in late August in Geneva.
UN experts have launched an investigation into reports of the use of chemical weapons in the Syrian city of Aleppo.
The first information about the terrorist attack with the use of toxic gas, presumably chlorine, appeared on August 2.
Then the opposition said that in the area where the Russian military transport helicopter had been shot down the day before, the aircraft dropped bombs with poisonous substances, but in Moscow these charges were called a throw-in.
Later, the Ministry of Defense of Russia accused the opposition group "Nur al-Ad-Din al-Zinka" in the incident.
Soon it became known that there were two bombs filled with toxic gas.
This was confirmed by the BBC one of the victims.
"A few minutes later I smelled gas, started burning my eyes, it became difficult to breathe," the newspaper quotes the eyewitness.
As a result of the attack, at least 7 people were killed, 23 were hospitalized.
If the use of poison gas is confirmed by experts, the actions will be regarded as a war crime.
UN Special Envoy for Syria Staffan de Mistura told reporters: "Evidence that this really happened, a lot."
The inadmissibility of the use of chlorine for military purposes is prescribed in the Convention on the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons (CWC).
Despite the fact that all parties to the Syrian conflict deny the use of toxic gases, in 2015 human rights defenders recorded 35 cases of chlorine use by the Syrian army against the "moderate opposition".
The situation in Aleppo is complicated by the fact that shelling of its areas are conducted daily, and terrorists prevent the withdrawal of residents from the city.
According to Reuters, the UN expects from Russia to establish a "humanitarian pause" in hostilities.
The current regime of the daily three-hour lull in the organization is considered "insufficient to help almost 2 million civilians trapped in the trap."
Staff adviser Staffan de Mistura on humanitarian issues Jan Egeland said that a 48-hour ceasefire would be required every week to deliver aid and evacuate sick and wounded people from the city.
"We have to send bulk cargo with a column of trucks in the area where the roads are almost destroyed, and those that remain are mined," Mr. Egeland said. "But the Russian delegation confirmed its readiness to sit with us at the negotiating table."
Consultations in Geneva between representatives of the United States and Russia regarding the establishment of a "humanitarian pause" are continuing.
How did Russia open the "humanitarian windows" in Aleppo.
In the ongoing battle for Aleppo - the second largest Syrian city - on August 11 Russia announced the introduction of a three-hour ceasefire regime, which will operate daily from Thursday.
The creation of "humanitarian windows" is designed to provide conditions for the delivery of medicines, food and basic necessities to the city.
The decision of the Russian Defense Ministry was made against the backdrop of growing international pressure on Moscow demanding to curtail the military operation and facilitate the resumption of the negotiation process.
As a result of a series of explosions in the resorts of Thailand, killing four people.
Several explosions thundered in the south of Thailand on Friday morning.
As a result of the attack, four people were killed and 19 wounded.
The epicenter of the bombings fell on the city of Hua Hin.
Among the victims were ten foreigners, citizens of four states, Russians are not among them.
The responsibility for the incident has not yet been taken by any of the terrorist groups, but the Interior Ministry hastened to state that the Islamists are not involved in it.
Several people have already been detained on suspicion of organizing the explosions.
According to preliminary data from the local police, the scale and characteristics of the explosions indicate that they were directed against the country's military leaders.
Attacks occurred at popular tourist resorts, including Patong Beach in the Phuket area and the city of Hua Hin, Trang and Surat Thani.
After the arrival of the military junta to power in the country in 2014, economic growth fell from 7.2% (2012) to 2.8% (2015), but tourism remained one of the few industries that demonstrated development.
In 2016, the country has already been visited by 14 million people, which is 1.5 million more than in 2015.
The first suspects in the preparation and organization of attacks have already been detained, Colonel Chris Patanacharenen said.
It is too early to talk about goals, he added, but the Interior Ministry "is sure that they are not connected with international extremist groups."
It's too early to draw conclusions, "Mr. Patanacharen said."
But we know for sure that these incidents are not directly related to any types of terrorism, in fact they are local sabotage, and we are trying to identify the identities of those who stood behind them.
Explosions occurred on the birthday of the Queen of Thailand Sikrit.
The Thai junta considers the protection of the monarchy to be one of its main priorities, therefore, the incident is most likely directed against it.
According to the statement of General of Police Sitkhichai Srinipacharenorata, the bombs were detonated remotely with a difference of half an hour.
They were hidden inside the trees in busy streets filled with dining in restaurants by tourists.
It is already known that one of the four victims was a Thai girl who sold street food.
The identity of the other victims is still unknown, but it is known that they are residents of four foreign countries.
According to the Royal Thai police, among them four German citizens, three Dutch nationals, two Italian citizens and an Austrian citizen.
Russians are not among the victims of the explosions, the press service of Rosturizm reported.
Local experts also link the explosions with the August 7 referendum, in which 61.4% of the country's population supported the draft of the new constitution.
It was prepared by the commission for drafting the constitution, appointed by the military junta.
Voters needed to decide whether they supported the system in which the upper house of parliament was fully appointed by the military and had a significant role in the election of the country's prime minister.
The new system was adopted and will be tested for the first time in the 2017 parliamentary elections.
Recall, on May 22, 2014 in Thailand, a military coup took place under the leadership of army commander Prajuta Chan-Och.
This step, he said, was fueled by an unceasing political crisis and a lack of progress in the negotiations between the government and the opposition.
The military created the National Council for Peace and Order, imposed a curfew and censorship, dispersed the protesters and the upper house of parliament.
How Bangkok found himself in a state of emergency
The Government of Thailand, led by Prime Minister Yinglak Shinawatra in January 2014, announced the imposition of a state of emergency in Bangkok and the provinces adjacent to the capital.
The special regime lasted 60 days.
As in Bangkok, two explosions boomed.
In January 2014, two explosions occurred in the center of Bangkok near the Victory Monument, where one of the main protests took place, as a result of which 28 people were injured, five of them were in critical condition.
Explosions were carried out by unknown persons on motorcycles.
The authorities stepped up security measures in the capital and enlisted the military to protect the demonstrators.
In the Dry Log the development of conditions began.
As it became known to Kommersant, the government was offered to agree on the draft terms of the auction for the Sukhoi Log gold deposit with the preservation of two key restrictions.
The auction is proposed not to allow a company where 25% or more belongs to foreigners, and those applicants in whose capital there will not be a minimum of 25% of state participation.
Industry participants do not expect that the government will rewrite the terms, noting that many players do not risk taking on a complex and expensive project.
The auction can be announced in August and held in October.
The Ministry of Natural Resources submitted to the government a draft order and auction terms for the largest undeveloped gold ore deposit in Russia, Sukhoi Log (Irkutsk region, reserves and resources - 130 million ounces), two sources told Kommersant that are familiar with the situation.
The project was introduced on Wednesday evening, one of them specifies.
The Ministry of Natural Resources confirmed to Kommersant that the project was submitted to the government.
A representative of the subsoil use supervisor, Deputy Prime Minister Alexander Khloponin, told Kommersant that the project had not yet been submitted to the office of an official.
"The auction can be announced already in August, immediately after the release of the government's order, and taking into account the deadline for the collection of applications of potential participants (at least 45 days), the tender can be held already in October," the Ministry said.
According to Kommersant's information, the project retained two key requirements for potential participants, which were prescribed in the version that was sent for approval to the ministries and federal agencies in July (Kommersant has).
First - the presence in the capital of applicants at least 25% of the state.
The second is the denial of access to the auction for companies under the control of foreign investors, based on the understanding of FZ-57 on foreign investment in strategic societies.
According to the two articles of the Federal Law specified in the draft law, as August 2 has already written to Kommersant, the company, whose beneficiaries (25% of shares and above) are not tax residents of the Russian Federation or have dual citizenship, can not be admitted to the auction.
The government has the right to impose such restrictions, as the Dry Log refers to the subsoil of federal significance (reserves of over 50 tons of gold).
The Ministry of Natural Resources confirmed that the project "contains restrictions on the admission of foreign companies," but declined to comment on details until the government decreed.
The demand for state participation in the capital of the participants in the auction was put forward by the Irkutsk region, they said to Kommersant in December 2015, and was later confirmed by regional governor Sergei Levchenko, noting that it was sent to the Ministry of Natural Resources by his predecessor, Sergey Eroshchenko, "who had agreements on investment projects with Rostekh."
Who lobbied the restriction on the admission of foreigners, the interlocutors of "Kommersant" do not specify.
"But it's in the spirit of the times: do not give the same control in the largest gold deposit in Russia against the backdrop of Western sanctions," - says the source of Kommersant, who is familiar with the preparation of the auction.
The head of the Ministry of Natural Resources Sergey Donskoy said on August 1 that foreigners "can go to the consortium" if the candidates attract them "as a financial structure, technological partners."
The interlocutors of Kommersant believe that it is unlikely that the government will correct the conditions.
The main contender for Sukhoi Log in the industry is the consortium of Russia's largest gold miner PJSC Polyus, controlled by the son of Suleiman Kerimov Said, and Rostekha.
As Kommersant wrote, in July partners created a joint venture "SL Gold", where Polyus holds 51% of shares, Rostelekh RT-GR has 49%.
Rostekha declined to comment, Polyusa told Kommersant that it "is certainly interested in this asset" and has all the necessary competencies and resources for its development.
"But the final decision on the possibility and format of our participation will be taken after the announcement of the conditions," - added to the "Pole".
ALROSA may participate in the auction, but the decision is made by the Russian government, sources told Kommersant.
The possibility of participating in the development of the Dry Log declared the Russian GV Gold and the Canadian Kinross, which develops assets in Chukotka, while Polymetal and Nordgold, according to Kommersant, are not interested in the asset.
The head of the Union of Gold Miners of the Russian Federation, Sergey Kashuba, in December 2015 estimated Kommersant's investments in Sukhoi Log at $ 2.5-4 billion.
Most potential contenders scare away not only the amount of investments, but also the complexity of the project: serious additional exploration of reserves and technologies for working with complex ores are needed, Kommersant's interlocutors in the industry explain.
