WSJ notes that the US usually prefers not to specify those who carry out hacker attacks.
The exception is the hacking of the database of Sony Entertainment Pictures, made in 2014, which was officially blamed on the DPRK.
However, last year Obama issued a decree simplifying the procedure for imposing sanctions on those who implement or promote cyberattacks.
Initially, it was directed against China, but it can also be used against other countries.
The process of deciding on sanctions can be lengthy, the newspaper writes.
Even if officials came to the conclusion that hackers acted with the support of Russia, before deciding to disclose information, they would have to weigh the possible consequences.
They will have to determine whether the incident is so serious, so as to aggravate the tension in bilateral relations because of it.
Earlier it was reported that the administration of Barack Obama allows the possibility of applying sanctions against the state, hackers who hacked the servers of the National Committee of the Democratic Party.
The WikiLeaks website published an electronic correspondence of the National Committee of Democrats.
