Military leadership distorted intelligence about IGIL, reports the Congressional Commission
Officials from the Central Command of the US Armed Forces have changed intelligence reports to present a more optimistic picture of the war against the Islamic state in Iraq and Syria, what is the basis for the events on the ground, the congressional commission said in a report released on Thursday.
The interim report of the task force, established by the Republican Presidents of the House Committee of the House of Representatives, the Intelligence Committee and the Military Appropriations Subcommittee, found "widespread discontent" among intelligence analysts of the Central Command, who claim that the leaders corrected their assessments of American actions aimed at defeating the Islamic state.
The central command, known as the Center, is the main military administration in Tampa, Florida, which controls American military operations in the Middle East and Central Asia.
"The reconnaissance documents approved by the central command of the Centcom, as a rule, gave a more optimistic picture of the US anti-terrorist actions than confirmed by real data from the scene, and were consistently more optimistic than the analysis provided by other special services," the news release said.
"What happened at the Centcom was unacceptable: when top management appears to be untrue, our military personnel are suffering," said Ken Calvert, a Republican from California, a member of the House of Representatives.
The problems with the leadership in the Centcom have reached the very top of the organization.
The ten-page report details the shortcomings that have constantly emerged in 2014 and 2015 in describing and analyzing American actions aimed at training the Iraqi armed forces provided by the Central Command.
Although it does not contain definitive evidence that members of the Obama administration have ordered to falsify reports, he argues that analysts felt that the leadership of the Centcom has forced them to present a more optimistic view of the threat posed by an Islamic state, also known as IGIL or ISIL.
"Throughout the first half of 2015, many of the press releases, statements and testimony of the Central Command in Congress were significantly more optimistic than real events," the report said.
For example, the official of the Centcom publicly stated that a major military attack aimed at the return of Mosul could begin in April or May 2015.
Mosul, the second largest city in Iraq, remains under the control of the Islamic state.
"After months of investigation, this is known for certain," said Rep. Mike Pompeo, a Republican from Kansas, in a statement.
From mid-2014 until mid-2015, the highest management of the Intelligence Service of the US Central Command forged intelligence command documents in order to downplay the threat from IGIL in Iraq.
Republicans created an operational group when they learned that analysts expressed concern that intelligence about the Islamic State was falsified.
As the investigation progresses, the report, published on Thursday, will be followed by more detailed data.
The additional, not completed at the moment investigation of the intelligence of the Center is conducted by the Chief Inspector of the Ministry of Defense.
Representatives of the Democratic Party in the Committee on Intelligence of the House of Representatives of the US Congress published their own data on Thursday, which are in line with some of the conclusions of the republican task force.
"Between 2014 and 2015, the Center created an overly-closed procedure for the production of intelligence assessments concerning IGIL and Iraqi security forces," said member of the House of Representatives Adam B. Schiff, the main representative of the Democratic Party in the committee.
This procedure, according to Schiff, "stalled the release of intelligence documents," damaged the morale of analysts and "does not reflect enough divergent views."
But Schiff and the Democrats say they have found no evidence that the White House tried to force the Centcom analysts to fit their conclusions into a "given or political interpretation."
Preliminary results of the investigation of the Congress were presented on Tuesday by the portal The Daily Beast.
Last August, The New York Times reported on the existence of an investigation by the Pentagon's chief inspector, who was opened after complaints from Centcom's analysts.
Lieutenant Commander Patrick Evans, a Pentagon spokesman, said in a statement that the Defense Ministry will not comment on the report of the congress while the investigation of the chief inspector is ongoing.
But he said that "experts sometimes disagree on the interpretation of complex data, and the intelligence services and the Ministry of Defense welcome a healthy dialogue on these vital issues relating to national security."
The consequences of the investigation go beyond the question of whether the targets pursued by the Americans are bombarded in Iraq and Syria (as now more and more representatives of the Ministry of Defense).
But last year's statements make us wonder whether President Obama can rely on the Central Command to provide truthful estimates of military operations in Iraq, Afghanistan, Libya and other crisis points.
Criticism of intelligence on the Islamic state repeats the disputes that took place more than ten years ago when the analyst of the intelligence service of the Centcom Gregory Hooker wrote a research article stating that the administration of President George Walker, because of the protest of many analysts, supported a small number of troops in Iraq and did not think about what would follow the 2003 invasion.
Hooker also played a key role in the protest, sparked by intelligence on the Islamic state.
Last year, according to officials, Hooker's team concluded that despite public statements to the contrary, air strikes against oil refineries belonging to the Islamic state did not lead to a significant deterioration in the financial situation of the terrorist group because it built temporary refineries to sell oil on the black market.
But the discovery was not extended outside the Central Command, as the Times reported in September.
The then commander of the Centcom, General Lloyd J. Austin III, was criticized last year after witness testimony in the Senate, which many deputies considered an overly optimistic assessment of the war.
General Austin resigned in April and was replaced in the Central Command by General Joseph L. Vautel.
