"Generation protests" in Ethiopia, a longtime US ally
Violent protests in Ethiopia
Demonstrators demanding political change in Ethiopia, faced with fierce opposition from the government.
Eyewitnesses say that dozens of protesters were fatally wounded during clashes with the police.
Is Ethiopia on the verge of schism?
Over the past decade, it has been one of the most stable countries in Africa, a firm ally of the West with a booming economy.
But in recent months, anti-government protests have shocked the country, spreading to an increasing number of its territories.
Only in the last week, thousands of people took to the streets, demanding radical political changes.
According to the defenders of human rights, the government's reaction was brutal.
Eyewitnesses claimed that police officers shot dozens of unarmed demonstrators.
The videotapes from the protests, allegedly filmed at the end of the past or the beginning of this year, show how security officers beat young people with sticks when they put their hands against the wall.
The United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights now calls for a thorough investigation.
"It has always been difficult to keep this country from disintegration, and further it will be even more difficult," said Rashid Abdi, the head of the project "The African Horn" in an international research crisis group.
Ethiopia is the second most populous country in Africa after Nigeria, and its stability is supported by the West.
The US military and intelligence services work closely with Ethiopians to combat terrorist threats in the region, especially in Somalia, and virtually no country in Africa receives such support from the West.
The economy of Ethiopia is developing at an impressive rate.
Its infrastructure has significantly improved - there is even a new suburban train in the capital Addis Ababa.
And its streets, as a rule, are quiet, safe and clean.
However, Ethiopia was hardly a model of democracy - human rights organizations constantly mention government reprisals - the opposition on the territory of the state was suppressed, due to the fact that dissidents were actually silenced.
Many of them were exiled, imprisoned, killed or expelled to remote deserts.
But this can change.
"If people are constantly suppressed and do not leave them other options than to protest, an uprising will take place," said Seium Teshome, a lecturer at the university in central Ethiopia.
All the young people are protesting.
Generation protests.
Complaints are numerous, ranging from land use to the seizure of power by a government coalition.
After widely criticized elections last year, the government party and its allies completely superseded the opposition and now control 100 percent of the Parliament.
At the same time, tension along the border with Eritrea is growing, the struggle for this vague, controversial border has claimed hundreds of lives in June.
Analysts fear that the separatist groups that have been more or less destroyed in recent years, such as the Oromo Liberation Front or the Ogaden National Liberation Front, may try to use excitement and rearm.
A number of factors explain why bitter feelings, boiling in the depths of one's soul for several years, are breaking out now.
The first, it would seem, is completely harmless: smartphones.
Only in the last couple of years a large number of Ethiopians have been able to communicate in social networks, since cheap smartphones have become commonplace, and Internet service has become better.
Even when the government closes access to Facebook and Twitter, as it often happens, especially during protests, many people still find the opportunity to communicate through proxy servers that hide where they are.
Several young Ethiopians said that this was how they organized themselves for protests.
The second is that there is more solidarity between Oromo and Amhara, the two largest Ethiopian ethnic groups.
Oromo and Amhara are not natural allies.
Over the centuries, Amhara from predominantly Christian high-mountainous regions of Ethiopia flourished in politics and business, exploiting Oromo, many of which are Muslim and live in low-lying areas.
But this is also changing.
"We will act together under a single principle," said Mulatu Gemechu, leader of Oromo.
The largest protests took place in the districts of Amhara and Oromo.
Many of Amhara and Oromo feel that members of the Tigray ethnic group, which is about 6 percent of the population, are unjustly dominant in Ethiopia, and which controls military and intelligence services, trade and politics.
The third reason for the unrest is the loss of Meles Zenawi.
Meles, a former rebel leader, served as Prime Minister of Ethiopia for 17 years, until his death from an unknown disease in 2012.
He was considered a tactical genius, a man who could foresee danger.
Analysts say that he especially skillfully recognized the first signals of discontent and used scouts to obtain data and neutralize opponents.
"The current regime lacks common sense," said Abdi, an analyst of conflict situations.
The new Prime Minister of Ethiopia, Hailemariam Desaleni, appeared from nowhere and took the place of Meles.
Unlike Meles, who was from Tigray in northern Ethiopia, Hailemariyam is a Southerner.
Analysts say he does not enjoy the confidence of security services controlled by Tigray.
Many fear that as a result this will lead to even greater bloodshed.
The last time Ethiopia survived such unrest in 2005, after thousands of people protested against what analysts said was apparently the election that the government mishandled, and then forged the results.
During the ensuing repressions, many Protestants were killed, albeit in a smaller number than in recent months, and this period of unrest was relatively rapid.
Development experts expressed their gratitude to the leaders of Ethiopia for the far-sighted development of infrastructure, such as a new inter-city train and significant successes in the fight against poverty.
But it is obvious that this did not stop the growth of internal dissatisfaction with the Ethiopian government.
And it takes a dangerous ethnic form.
Last month, protesters in Gondar, a city in Amhar, attacked businesses owned by Tigray, and anti-Tigray's hate on social networks became all-inclusive.
Analysts say that the protesters put the United States and other Western allies in an uncomfortable position.
The US government used Ethiopia as a base for unmanned flights over neighboring Somalia, although it recently announced that it closed the base.
On the one hand, it is clear that the West wants to support democracy, but on the other hand, it does not want its ally to lose power in an already volatile region.
"And on this tight rope it will be difficult to pass," Abdi said.
