Depressive eating depression in the "Dense meal"
In March 1933, shortly after his ascent to the presidency, Franklin Delano Roosevelt sat down to dine in the Oval Office.
Being a gourmet, President Roosevelt loved Fifth Avenue's fashion dishes, for example, foie gras and Maryland turtle soup.
His menu on this day was more modest: stuffed eggs in tomato sauce, mashed potatoes and for dessert - a prune pudding.
"It was an act of culinary solidarity with people who suffered," said Jane Siegelman.
Her husband Andrew Coe added: "It was also a message to Americans about how to eat."
Spouses living in Brooklyn Heights, are experts in the history of food.
