Their new collaboration, The Dense Meal, which will be published Tuesday by Harper, is the story of American food for the Great Depression.
Manifesting to some extent his own culinary solidarity, they met with a reporter for dinner at the Eisenberg's Sandwich Shop, a tiny simple diner in the Flatiron neighborhood, which has been operating since 1929, the year of the Market Crash.
Zigelman, 54, ordered a cream cheese and a sandwich with slices of olives, and Coe, 57, took a turkey, mashed potatoes and a vegetable mix.
When the reporter ordered a meatloaf, the pair considered this a suitable starting point for discussion about food in the Depression era.
"Rolls were in high demand," Siegelman said.
There was peanut roll, liver roll, bean roll.
They were made from a basic ingredient and cheap products that allowed to stretch the ingredient.
Imagine that you ate as much peanuts as you need for dinner.
Coe winced.
"He must have been lying in the stomach with a stone," he said.
In the years before the Depression, the American table, especially in the countryside, was a buffet.
Groups of women prepared for male farm workers, and freshly baked cake was served for breakfast, lunch and dinner.
It was the Americans who sent food to the starving Europeans during the First World War.The "tight meal" describes how the country coped with the fact that it suddenly ceased to be a country of plenty.
"It was a time when food became a central, uneasy topic for Americans," Coe said, explaining why he and his wife decided to write about it.
Equally challenging was the new budget ration: mysterious dishes such as rolls and casseroles became the staple food, casserole is "an excellent way to utilize scraps," said Siegelman, "because cooks could hide unappetizing ingredients under a thick layer of sauce."
Fresh fruit was replaced with cheaper dried fruits.
