Scientists from the NASU Space Research Institute Goddard developed a model for exploring the past of Venus, using tools and algorithms similar to those used by climatologists.
The model was designed to determine whether Venus, with its hot waterless surface and carbon-saturated atmosphere, could ever have had conditions similar to that of the earth.
Scientists previously assumed that the small speed of rotation of Venus is due to its dense atmosphere.
But the latest simulation suggests that Venus probably could have a rarefied atmosphere, similar to the terrestrial, and still rotate slowly.
The model also considered the topography of the early Venus.
On the planet, in all probability, there were more arid regions than on Earth, but once it had enough water and enough geographical variability to create conditions for life and prevent rapid evaporation.
Early Venus also benefited the sun, which was 30 percent duller.
"According to the GISS model, the slow rotation of Venus substitutes its day side of the sun for almost two months at a time," the GISS scientist Anthony Del Henio explained in a press release.
It warms the surface of the planet and produces rain, which creates a thick layer of clouds, acting as an umbrella, protecting the planet's surface from a significant part of the sun's heat.
The result is average climatic temperatures, which, surprisingly, are several degrees colder than in our days on Earth.
The model shows the history of Venus, similar to the development, which was previously assumed by specialists in the study of planets.
Despite the fact that once Venus may have been inhabited, it has been exposed to too much heat and ultraviolet radiation for several billion years.
Its oceans evaporated and its water vapor was burned by ultraviolet radiation.
When her hydrogen evaporated, there was only a dense atmosphere of carbon dioxide with a deadly greenhouse effect - that is, Venus, as we know it today.
Researchers shared the results of their new climate model of Venus in the journal Geophysical Research Letters.
