Kepler measures the rotation speed of stars in the Pleiades cluster
The last mission of the space telescope Kepler helped astronomers to compile the most complete catalog of the rotation speeds of stars entering the Pleiades cluster.
The new data helps astronomers understand why stars in a cluster rotate at different speeds, and how the periods of rotation correlate with the formation of planets.
"We hope that by comparing our results with other star clusters, we will learn more about the relationship between the mass of the star, its age and even the history of its solar system," said Louise Riball, a researcher at the Center for Infrared Processing and Analysis at the California Institute of Technology.
The Pleiades cluster is 445 light years from Earth.
Many of the stars in the cluster now only reach maturity, they were born about 125 million years ago.
They rotate as fast as they never will again.
At their peak rotation speeds, these maturing stars emit large amounts of stellar wind.
Traveling through the magnetic fields of stars, these winds exert a retarding effect on the stars.
As the star ages its rotation speed begins to slow down.
Kepler measures the speed of rotation of each star, tracking the time between the appearance of recognizable stellar spots - such as sunspots.
The newest catalog of speeds of rotation forces to assume that more massive stars rotate more slowly, than less massive stars.
Riball compares stars with dancers: larger ones make pirouettes slower than smaller ones.
"In the Pleiades ballet, we see that those that rotate slowly are usually more massive, whereas those that rotate faster usually refer to very light stars," Riball said.
Since the Pleiades cluster is so close, it serves as an ideal space laboratory for comparing the properties of stars with the velocities of rotation.
"The star cluster of the Pleiades provides a starting point for theoretical models of rotation of stars, both younger and older," Riball said.
We still want to learn a lot about how, where and why the stars slow their speed of rotation and hang their "dance shoes" on the nail, figuratively speaking.
Riball and her colleagues elaborated on their latest analysis of the Pleiadian rotation speeds in three new articles that will soon be published in the Astronomical Journal.
