Sandwiched between Angola and South Africa, Namibia suffered greatly during the long struggle against apartheid.
Nevertheless, after gaining independence from South Africa in 1990, this country with a population of 2.4 million people has made tremendous progress, especially in the last few years.
The main reason for Namibia's success is that the government pays great attention to education.
While people in developed countries take for granted free primary and secondary education, many poor countries in middle and even primary schools require tuition fees.
Moreover, governments are often advised to introduce fee training for "cost recovery".
