Efforts to eradicate malaria have reduced the number of annual cases of disease by 97% in the last ten years.
Contrary to the international trend of rising inequality, in Namibia it is declining.
Compared with the 1993 indicator, the Gini coefficient, which is the standard measure of income inequality, dropped by 15 points.
Then, 23 years ago, this indicator was one of the highest in the world.
And the poverty level declined from 69% in 1993 to less than 30%.
The number of people living in extreme poverty (less than $ 1.90 per day) also declined, from almost 53% to less than 23%.
Namibia also has the highest freedom of speech rating in Africa, according to "Reporters Without Borders."
The country was much ahead of the United States and other rich states.
