Even now, when commodity prices are falling, Namibia manages to maintain high growth rates.
At the same time, the ratio of debt to GDP is about 25%, which is less than 1/3 of the debt level in the US and most European countries.
Of course, Namibia also has some problems.
The unemployment rate, at least according to the traditional methods of assessment, still remains quite high - almost 28%.
And, like other countries in the region, Namibia has a high incidence of HIV / AIDS - almost 17% of the population is infected.
The World Bank estimates that Namibia is among the countries with above-average income, but the authorities insist that their state is in fact a developing country.
Namibia, of course, faces some difficulties that are inherent in poorly developed economies.
The state has to develop a very large and arid country with a small population.
On the territory of the country, isolated nomadic tribes of hunter-gatherers live in deserts, which somehow should be integrated into modern society, without losing their identity.
Integration of people who were a quarter of a century ago were on the periphery of the world economy is not an easy task for any country.
For Namibia, this is even more difficult: just like any other country in the world, it is facing the consequences of climate change.
However, Namibia did not think to give up, the country is solving the problems facing it.
Almost immediately after gaining independence, the authorities engaged in creating a diversified economy and a cohesive society.
It is noteworthy that competing political factions came together to work for the common good.
Indeed, Namibia provides cheap medical care not only to its own citizens, but also to its neighbors.
About 15-20% of visitors to medical institutions in the northern regions of Namibia are Angolan citizens.
No one in Namibia speaks of building a wall that would separate the country from poor and corrupt neighbors.
Namibians realized that they do not choose neighbors, and therefore they decided not to conflict with them, but to cooperate - to share scarce water resources, to take part in regional medical projects, to encourage investments and exchange of students.
In addition, the government of Namibia rightly reasoned that rich natural resources can easily become a curse, contributing to the enrichment of the few at the expense of many.
The authorities understand that the income from the natural resources of Namibia needs to be invested in infrastructure and production facilities.
They also realize that it would be irresponsible not to seek maximum profit from the sale of the country's resources, and revise investment laws and production contracts to make sure that this is so.
Transparency is crucial for this process, so strong government support for freedom of speech is so important.
As the head of state Hage Geynog noted, the media often say something that he does not like.
But after the struggle for freedom from apartheid in South Africa, Namibia must protect the freedoms, the president says.
Not all the key resources of Namibia are exhaustible.
Some - such as fishing - are considered renewable, and the government is making every effort to preserve and strengthen them.
Every year more than a million foreign tourists visit the country.
Namibia shows that even those countries that start with serious shortcomings - racism, colonialism, inequality and low development - can embark on a path to overall prosperity.
Its achievement deserves international recognition and imitation.
Many heard about the "Gold of Varna" - the oldest gold objects created by man (4600 - 4200 BC).
Perhaps it was the loudest archaeological sensation of the 1970s: in Bulgaria, during the excavation of the Varna necropolis, a fantastic amount of gold artifacts was found - more than three thousand with a total weight of 6 kilograms.
Only one grave, known as "grave number 43", was extracted 990 gold items totaling more than 1.5 kg.
However, the official status of the world's oldest gold can soon pass to a plain-looking bead found by archaeologists in July this year.
And again in Bulgaria - in a prehistoric settlement, known as Tell Yunatsite.
Unlike Varna, the port city, Tell Yunatsite is located far from the sea, near the village of Yunatsite, Pazardzhik district.
The bead is a golden strip, folded into a ring.
Yavor Boyadzhiev, the head of the excavation at Telle Yunatsite, dated the find in 4600 BC and stated that it is over the gold of Varna for at least 200 years.
The treasures of Varna, we recall, date back approximately the same period, 4600 - 4200 BC.
The technology, allowing to accurately date the metal, does not currently exist.
Where does the confidence in what kind of gold is more ancient?
Obviously, Professor Boyadzhiev knows more than told Reuters: "I'm absolutely sure that gold is more than the gold of Varna."
This is a finding of extreme importance: in appearance this is a tiny subject, however it is large enough to occupy a proper place in history.
In an interview with Reuters Boyadzhiyev said that in the near future, scientists will analyze the composition of the metal, as well as repeatedly and more carefully study the archaeological stratum, where a gold artifact was found.
This will help date the bead as accurately as possible.
The location of the find also explains a lot.
Tell Yunatsite is a famous settlement, even if you have never heard of it.
Currently, Tell Yunatsite is considered the oldest "city" of Europe.
Tell was founded by descendants of people who migrated to Europe from Anatolia (modern Turkey) in the 7th millennium BC.
During the following centuries, metal processing was rapidly developing in this region, from the development of the first metallurgical skills to the creation of a full-fledged industry.
In the domestic historiography for this archaeological community there is a special name: the Balkan-Carpathian metallurgical province.
In the 5th millennium BC, urban-type settlements began to appear around metal processing centers.
Now they are called the oldest cities in Europe.
Among them, Tell Yunatsite is perhaps the oldest, since artifacts of 4,900 BC were found here.
I would call Tell Yunatsite the prototype of a modern city, although it is a very ancient settlement, even compared to Mesopotamia.
"This place is older than Sumer for a thousand years," says Boyadjiev, referring to the generally accepted view that urban culture originated in southern Mesopotamia - modern Iraq.
There the first cities appeared in the usual sense of the word.
Excavations of Tell Yunatsite have been conducted since 1976.
During this time, archaeologists excavated almost 12 hectares, this is about a third of the estimated total area of the settlement.
The remains of the fortress wall, which once reached three meters in height, were found.
From houses and workshops little has been preserved, but archaeologists clearly distinguish streets, public buildings, urban dense buildings, "business center" and residential outskirts.
Tell Yunatsite is often called the "Bird's City": dozens of clay figurines of birds were found here.
All birds are depicted in a state of rest, hence the assumption that they were not decorative objects, but the object of a local cult.
"Bird City" was destroyed around 4,400 BC - perhaps by Indo-European tribes that came from the north-east.
The nomads had no cities, but there were horses and weapons.
Three-meter-high fortress walls did not stop them.
Archaeologists have discovered obvious signs of a brutal massacre: inside the houses were found the remains of old men, women and children with traces of wounds inflicted with battle axes.
New finds and new facts appear every year, changing the usual ideas about the ancient history of mankind.
Bulgarian archeologists are increasingly talking not about individual cultures, but about the "lost" first civilization of Europe that originated in the Balkans.
A powerful stimulus in the search for this civilization was the "gold of Varna", found relatively recently, in 1972.
It is logical that the golden luxury of Varna should have something to precede - something like a tiny golden bead, created in Tella Yunatsite.
